{{short description|Regions where rivers debouch into estuaries and coastal shelf seas where the currents patterns are governed by density differences between salt sea water and fresh river water}}
'''Region of Freshwater Influence''' (ROFI), a term coined by Prof. John Simpson<ref>{{Cite web |url= http://www.sos.bangor.ac.uk/staff/php/staffdetails1.php?person=0022 |title= Biography |author= John Simpson |work=  |publisher= [[University of Wales, Bangor]] |accessdate= 2009-10-29 |deadurl= yes |archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20110716205120/http://www.sos.bangor.ac.uk/staff/php/staffdetails1.php?person=0022 |archivedate= 2011-07-16 |df=  }}</ref> of the [[University of Wales, Bangor]], and co-authors, in 1993 in Oceanologica Acta<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simpson |first1= J.H.|last2= Bos|first2= W.G. |author3=F. Shirmer |author4=A.J. Souza |author5=T.P. Rippeth |author6=S.E. Jones |author7=D. Hydes|year= 1993|title= Periodic stratification in the Rhine ROFI in the North Sea|journal= Oceanologica Acta|volume= 16|issue= 1|pages= 23–32|url= |doi= }}</ref> for the [[Rhine]] river plume. The term refers to regions where [[river]]s [[debouch]] into [[estuary|estuaries]] and coastal [[shelf sea]]s where the currents patterns are governed by density differences between salt [[sea water]] and fresh river water. In other words, a ROFI is the region between the shelf sea regime and the estuary where the local input of freshwater buoyancy from the coastal source is comparable with, or exceeds, the seasonal input of buoyancy as heat which occurs all over the shelf.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Simpson |first1= J.H.|last2= |first2= |year= 1997|title= Physical processes in the ROFI regime|journal= Journal of Marine Systems|volume= |issue= 12|pages= 3–15|url= |doi= }}</ref> Americans usually use the term river plume where Europeans use ROFI.

